data: {"type":"response.output_text.done","sequence_number":304,"item_id":"msg_025833c0508fc6330069177bfecc3c8194bb1606aa491977cb","output_index":1,"content_index":0,"text":"A \"steam reactor\" can mean different things depending on context. Here are the two common meanings:\n\n1) In power generation / nuclear context\n- Informally, people use “steam reactor” to describe a reactor system that produces steam to drive a turbine. Two typical configurations:\n  - Boiling Water Reactor (BWR): the reactor core boils the reactor coolant directly; the generated steam goes straight to the turbine.\n  - Pressurized Water Reactor (PWR) with steam generator: the reactor heats a primary coolant under pressure (so it doesn’t boil); that hot fluid transfers heat in a steam generator to a secondary loop where water turns to steam for the turbine.\n- Key idea: the reactor’s heat is converted into steam, and the steam expands in a turbine to make electricity.\n\n2) In chemical / process engineering (steam reforming)\n- A “steam reactor” can be a chemical reactor where steam reacts with a feedstock (e.g., methane steam reforming) over a catalyst to produce other chemicals (e.g., hydrogen and carbon monoxide):\n  CH4 + H2O (steam) → CO + 3 H2 (over Ni catalyst at high T)\n- Key idea: steam participates as a reactant and the reactor is designed for high temperatures, catalysts, and gas flows.\n\nIf you mean another specific device (a boiler, steam generator, supercritical steam reactor, or a particular reactor type), tell me which and I’ll give more detail.","logprobs":[]}

